  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nScope note: this is a pure Python/SQLite batch pipeline (125 configured sources in `sources.yaml`, run via `pipeline.py`/`agent.py`) — there's no React or any frontend code in the repo, so that section doesn't apply. I focused the equivalent effort on the DB layer, filtering, and the async fetchers instead.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (the big one)\n\n`Store.diff()` issues one `SELECT` per job, in a Python loop, for every job fetched this run:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n        ...\n```\n\nWith 125 sources (several paginating up to 400+ roles — Microsoft, Amazon, Google, Netflix, Eightfold tenants), a single run can push several thousand individual round trips to SQLite just to check what's new. SQLite is in-process so each round trip is cheap individually, but it's still thousands of Python↔C calls plus query re-planning, and it'll get materially worse the moment this ever points at a networked DB.\n\n**Fix** — batch the lookup into one query, keep everything else the same:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):          # stay under SQLite's 999-var limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        qs = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        existing.update(\n            (r[\"key\"], r[\"content_hash\"])\n            for r in cur.execute(f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qs})\", chunk)\n        )\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                         [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round trips into O(N/900) + one `executemany`.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job in `filters.py`\n\n`filter_jobs()` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(include)`/`_compile(exclude)` **every time**:\n\n```python\n# filters.py:15-27\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every call\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\n`filter_jobs` runs this for every fetched job (thousands per run), so the same handful of keyword patterns get `re.compile`'d thousands of times over.\n\n**Fix** — compile once, pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None, ...):\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\n### 3. Caching opportunities\n\n- **No HTTP conditional requests.** Every run re-fetches full board payloads from scratch — `fetchers.py`'s `_request`/`_get_json` never send `If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since`, and responses' `ETag`/`Last-Modified` headers (where ATS platforms send them — Greenhouse/Lever/Ashby often do) are discarded. For a scraper that's presumably run on a schedule (per the `6h/12h scheduled run` commit history), that's a lot of wasted bandwidth/parse time on unchanged boards. Worth adding a small per-source cache of `(etag, body)` in the `meta` table, keyed by URL, and passing `If-None-Match` on the next run — skip parsing entirely on a 304.\n- **`Job.content_hash` is recomputed twice for every changed job** — once in `Store.diff()` for the comparison, once again inside `_update()` → `to_row()`. It's a cheap SHA-256 over a short string so not urgent, but since `Job` is `@dataclass(slots=True)` you can't use `functools.cached_property` directly; if you want to fix it, add an explicit `_content_hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False)` slot and memoize manually, or just compute the hash once in `diff()` and pass it into `_insert`/`_update` instead of recomputing.\n\n### 4. Memory leaks\n\nThis is a short-lived CLI/batch process (fetch → filter → diff → notify → exit), not a long-running server, so the classic \"unbounded growth over process lifetime\" leak doesn't really apply here — I didn't find one. Two things worth flagging as hygiene rather than leaks:\n- `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:1000-1021`) correctly closes the `httpx.AsyncClient` in a `finally` block only when it created the client itself — fine as written, just note that if a caller ever passes in its own `client`, they're responsible for closing it (already implied by `owns_client`, no action needed).\n- `notify.py`'s Slack/webhook/SMS notifiers each open a **fresh** `httpx.post()` (new connection, new TLS handshake) rather than reusing a client. Only fires once per run today, so it's not a leak, just a missed opportunity — not worth fixing unless notification volume grows.\n\n### 5. Other redundant computation\n\n- **Pagination fetchers do real parsing before dedup**, e.g. `fetch_twosigma`/`fetch_apple`/`fetch_amazon`/etc. all call `parse_X()` on the full page, *then* filter by `external_id not in seen`. This is necessary (dedup requires knowing the ids, which only exist post-parse) and the pages are small (10–20 items), so it's fine — flagging only so it's not mistaken for the N+1 pattern.\n- `agent.py`'s `cmd_db_new` already does the right thing (`store.added_since(since)` — a single indexed query, `ORDER BY first_seen`), unlike `store.diff()`. Worth using it as the template when fixing #1.\n\n### Priority\n1. Fix `Store.diff()` N+1 (#1) — highest impact, scales with job count (thousands/run).\n2. Hoist regex compilation in `filters.py` (#2) — cheap fix, same job-count scaling.\n3. HTTP conditional requests (#3) — bigger lift, worth it if this runs on a tight schedule against boards that barely change.\n4. Everything else is minor/optional.\n",
